# Fitness / Health Tracker — project checklist

Full rubric text lives in Canvas (“Project Deliverable Latest_GRAD”). Use this file as your working list; tick items as you go.

---

## Cleanup

- [x] Remove unused files, dead code, and dependencies not needed for submission

**How to verify:** Repo search for unused imports/routes; delete obvious junk; run the app and tests; ensure `README` only lists deps you actually use.

---

## Database (MySQL)

- [x] Every foreign key specifies `ON UPDATE` and `ON DELETE` (per rubric)
- [x] Table count meets group size (1→≥6, 2→≥9, 3→≥12); schema in 3NF
- [x] Primary keys on all tables; FKs (and UNIQUE where needed) match your ERD
- [x] Field/table constraints: NOT NULL, DEFAULT, etc., where appropriate
- [x] Server-side objects: procedures, functions, triggers (not all SQL in the client); add an event only if your rubric requires it
- [x] Self-contained dump: `CREATE`/`USE`, all objects, sample data; runs clean in a fresh MySQL

**How to verify:** Grep the schema/dump for `FOREIGN KEY` and confirm each has `ON UPDATE` and `ON DELETE`. Count tables. Open dump on a clean DB. In Workbench, reverse-engineer and compare to your logical design.

---

## Client application

- [ ] Working **CREATE** — new rows persist (check in Workbench/CLI)
- [ ] Working **READ** — data shown comes from the DB
- [ ] Working **UPDATE** — changes persist after refresh/reconnect
- [ ] Working **DELETE** — rows removed in the DB
- [ ] UI: clear prompts and feedback; flow is driven by user input
- [ ] Modularity: reusable functions/modules; lean client SQL, heavier use of DB objects where rubric expects it
- [ ] Error handling: bad input and DB errors handled without crashes

**How to verify:** For each CRUD type, do the action in the app, then confirm the same row(s) in MySQL Workbench (or `mysql` client). Try invalid input and disconnect DB briefly if you can do so safely.

---

## Submission package

- [ ] Zip: `groupname_project.zip` with schema dump, all app code, report (and presentation extras if any)
- [ ] Submission note includes **link to project video** (if required)
- [ ] Nothing missing: grader can build/run from README without chasing you for files

**How to verify:** Unzip on another machine or folder; follow README only; import dump; run app end-to-end.

---

## Report (PDF)

- [ ] README: install steps, libs, versions, expected paths
- [ ] Technical specifications (stack, frameworks)
- [ ] Conceptual design: ERD in **UML**
- [ ] Logical design: crow’s foot (e.g. Workbench reverse engineer)
- [ ] User activity / flow (text or diagram)
- [ ] Lessons learned + future work (and note anything broken, if applicable)
- [ ] File name: `canvas_group_name_final_report.pdf`

**How to verify:** Print or PDF review: every required section present; diagrams match the submitted schema.

---

## Video / presentation (5–7 min)

- [ ] Schema, architecture, and app purpose explained clearly (audio/video clear)
- [ ] **Three** CRUD demos (or two if first presentation day only — per your syllabus): for each, show DB client **before** → use app → show DB client **after** with the change highlighted
- [ ] All group members participate equally; logical flow through topics

**How to verify:** Dry run with a timer; record a practice take and watch once for gaps.

---

## Rubric pass (cross-check Canvas)

Work through Canvas row-by-row and mark below when satisfied:

**Video / deliverable meta**

- [ ] Data schema described (logical design matches data)
- [ ] CRUD demo + verification in a second client
- [ ] Application functionality described
- [ ] Presentation quality (see/hear/follow)
- [ ] Group participation
- [ ] Logical flow of video

**Submission**

- [ ] Complete: DB objects + frontend + runnable dump + sample data + README; no post-deadline rescue needed

**DB criteria**

- [ ] Complexity / 3NF / minimum tables for group size
- [ ] PKs and FKs (relationships) complete
- [ ] FKs fully specified (`ON UPDATE` / `ON DELETE`)
- [ ] Field and table constraints
- [ ] Database programming objects (quantity/quality per rubric)

**Client criteria**

- [ ] Completeness of CRUD coverage across entities/tables
- [ ] User interface usability
- [ ] CREATE / READ / UPDATE / DELETE each working as defined
- [ ] Modularity (host language + DB objects)
- [ ] Robustness / error handling

**Report criteria**

- [ ] Conceptual (UML) and logical (crow’s foot) designs
- [ ] Document structure
- [ ] Lessons learned + future work
- [ ] User activity description
- [ ] README + technical description sections

**Bonus (optional, max 105/100)**

- [ ] Any planned bonus items documented/demonstrated

**How to verify:** Open the rubric in Canvas; for each row, point to evidence (file, demo timestamp, diagram page). No evidence → leave unchecked until you add it.

---

## Wrap-up

- [ ] Front-end polish and any remaining UI work
- [ ] Debug open issues (track in issues list or short notes here)
- [ ] Final pass: run full verification above, then submit

**How to verify:** Same as sections above, done in order: DB → app → report → video → zip → Canvas checklist.
